On Monday, October 18, 2004, at 03:36PM, <ARoman4047(-at-)aol.com> wrote:

>Dielectric grease is an anti-corrosion lubricant that is conductive.

Anti-corrosion is correct but it's actually non-conductive. Only put it on an eletrical connection after the terminals have made contact.

>I use it all the time on every connector (even a dab on the top o'
>the spark plugs...;-) 

The connection is probably squeezing some grease away making metal to metal contact. The grease is mainly used to seal the spark plug boots in order keep water out.

